,"ei":15293,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":15312,"ei":16109,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#c5e1a5","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":16110,"ei":16125,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":16144,"ei":17089,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#ffb8a1","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":17090,"ei":17105,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime(, DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc"  nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc"  nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":17112,"s":"\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cVideo games took the traditional properties of potentially flow-inducing activities—a goal, obstacles, increasing challenge, and voluntary participation—and then used a combination of direct physical input (the joystick), flexible difficulty adjustment (the computer algorithms), and instant visual feedback (the video graphics) to tighten the feedback loop of games dramatically. And this faster, tighter feedback loop allowed for more reliable hits of the emotional reward fiero: each microlevel of difficulty you survived prompted a split-second emotional high\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c51\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cNo object, no event, no outcome or life circumstance can deliver real happiness to us. We have to make our own happiness—by working hard at activities that provide their own reward. 15 When we try to find happiness outside of ourselves, we’re focused on what positive psychologists call “extrinsic” rewards—money, material goods, status, or praise.\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c56\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOn the other hand, when we set out to make our own happiness, we’re focused on activity that generates intrinsic rewards—the positive emotions, personal strengths, and social connections that we build by engaging intensely with the world around us. We’re not looking for praise or payouts. The very act of what we’re doing, the enjoyment of being fully engaged, is enough. The scientific term for this kind of self-motivated, self-rewarding activity is autotelic (from the Greek words for “self,” auto , and “goal,” telos ). 17 We do autotelic work because it engages us completely, and because intense engagement is\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c56\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cindividuals who focused on intrinsically rewarding activity, working hard to develop their personal strengths and build social relationships, for example, were measurably happier over the entire two-year period completely regardless of external life circumstances like salary or social status.\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c57\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001chappiness derived from intrinsic reward is incredibly resilient. Every time we engage in autotelic activities, the very opposite of hedonic adaptation occurs. We wean ourselves off consumption and acquisition as sources of pleasure and develop our hedonic resilience . As research psychologist Sonja Lyubomirsky, a leading expert on intrinsic reward, explains: “One of the chief reasons for the durability of happiness activities is that . . . they are hard won. You’ve devoted time and effort.... You have made these practices happen, and you have the ability to make them happen again. This sense of capability and responsibility is a powerful boost in and of itself.” In other words, we become better able to protect and strengthen our quality of life, regardless of\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c57\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cBy accomplishing something that is very hard for us, like solving a puzzle or finishing a race, our brains release a potent cocktail of norepinephrine, epinephrine, and dopamine. These three neurochemicals in combination make us feel satisfied, proud, and highly aroused. 20 When we make someone else laugh or smile, our brain is flooded with dopamine, the neurotransmitter associated with pleasure and reward. If we laugh or smile, too, the effect is even more pronounced. 21 Every time we coordinate or synchronize our physical movements with others, such as in dance or sports, we release oxytocin into our bloodstream, a neurochemical that makes us feel blissed out and ecstatic. 22 When we seek out what we might describe as “powerful” and “moving” stories, media, or live performances, we’re actually triggering our vagus nerve, which makes us feel emotionally “choked up” in our chests and throats, or we’re firing up our nervous system’s pilomotor reflex, which gives us pleasurable chills and goose bumps. 23\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c58\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cFirst and foremost, we crave satisfying work , every single day. The exact nature of this “satisfying work” is different from person to person, but for everyone it means being immersed in clearly defined, demanding activities that allow us to see the direct impact of our efforts.\n\nApril 21, 2015\n\u001c60\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.33","spi":17121},{"ty":"te","id":"i.34","spi":17720},{"ty":"te","id":"i.35","spi":18104},{"ty":"te","id":"i.36","spi":18756},{"ty":"te","id":"i.37","spi":19085},{"ty":"te","id":"i.38","spi":19890},{"ty":"te","id":"i.39","spi":20943},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":17112,"ei":17112,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":17113,"ei":17113,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":17114,"ei":17114,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":468.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.75,"tbls_bc":"#bdbdbd"}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":17116,"ei":17116,"sm":{"cell_pb_i":false,"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_pb":0.0,"cell_pr":0.0,"cell_pl_i":false,"cell_pl":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":17118,"ei":17118,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":358.5,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":17120,"ei":17120,"sm":{"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_bl":{},"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_bb_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_bt":{},"cell_pb":0.0,"cell_pl_i":false,"cell_br":{},"cell_pb_i":false,"cell_bl_i":false,"cell_br_i":false,"cell_pr":0.0,"cell_bt_i":false,"cell_bb":{},"cell_pl":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":17122,"ei":17122,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":false,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_al":1,"ps_ifl_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":17123,"ei":17123,"sm":{"cell_pr_i":fal