,"ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":42057,"ei":42072,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":42092,"ei":42641,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#ffb8a1","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":42642,"ei":42657,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":42677,"ei":43298,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#c5e1a5","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":43299,"ei":43314,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime(, DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc"  nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc"  nonce="XLRXM48gzebsEp22wlL6FrhBZQc">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":43322,"s":"\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cHow do we get more meaning in our lives? It’s actually quite simple. Philosophers, psychologists, and spiritual leaders agree: the single best way to add meaning to our lives is to connect our daily actions to something bigger than ourselves —and the bigger, the better. As Martin Seligman says, “The self is a very poor site for meaning.” We can’t matter outside of a large-scale social context. “The larger the entity you can attach yourself to,” Seligman advises, “the more meaning you can derive.” 8\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c111\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cTo experience real meaning, we don’t have to contribute something of real value. We just have to be given the opportunity to contribute at all. We need a way to connect with others who care about the same massively scaled goal we do, no matter how arbitrary the goal. And we need a chance to reflect on the truly epic scale of what we’re doing together.\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c111\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cEpic is one of the most important concepts in gamer culture today. It’s how players describe their most memorable, gratifying game experiences. As one game critic writes, “ Halo 3 is epic. It empowers you the way no other game can. It doesn’t have moments, but events. Experiences that tickle the soul, sending shivers down the spine . ”\n\nLike 3 mag power plays at the same time! Paul Luke bo! Room destroyed\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c112\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cBlockbuster video games do epic scale better than any other medium of our time, and they’re epic in three key ways: They create epic contexts for action : collective stories that help us connect our individual gameplay to a much bigger mission. They immerse us in epic environments : vast, interactive spaces that provoke feelings of curiosity and wonder. And they engage us in epic projects : cooperative efforts carried out by players on massive scales, over months or even year\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c112\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cAwe is a unique emotion. According to many positive psychologists, it’s the single most overwhelming and gratifying positive emotion we can feel. In fact, neuropsychologist Paul Pearsall calls awe “the orgasm of positive emotions.” 11\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c112\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cAwe is what we feel when we recognize that we’re in the presence of something bigger than ourselves. It’s closely linked with feelings of spirituality, love, and gratitude—and more importantly, a desire to serve.\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c112\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cThe experience of awe is about finding your place in the larger scheme of things. It is about quieting the press of self-interest. It is about folding into social collectives. It is about feeling reverential toward participating in some expansive process that unites us all and that ennobles our life’s endeavors.” 12 In other words, awe doesn’t just feel good; it inspires us to do good\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c113\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cSpine tingling is one of the classic physiological symptoms of awe—along with chills, goose bumps, and that choked-up feeling in the throat\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c113\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001calways connect the individual to something bigger.\n\nCan grow be a competition - where we r aiming for mutually assured awesomeness\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c113\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001c“When games give players the epic scope of saving the galaxy, destroying some reawakened ancient evil, or any other classical portrayal of good versus evil on a grand scale, they’re fulfilling gamers’ power fantasies.” 13\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c114\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cNot every game feels like a larger cause. For a game to feel like a cause , two things need to happen. First, the game’s story needs to become a collective context for action—shared by other players, not just an individual experience. That’s why truly epic games are always attached to large, online player communities—hundreds of thousands or millions of players acting in the same context together, and talking to each other\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c115\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cthe actions that players take inside the collective context need to feel like service: every effort by one player must ultimately benefit all the other players. In other words, every individual act of gameplay has to eventually add up to something bigger.\n\nApril 22, 2015\n\u001c115\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.83","spi":43331},{"ty":"te","id":"i.84","spi":43871},{"ty":"te","id":"i.85","spi":44261},{"ty":"te","id":"i.86","spi":44706},{"ty":"te","id":"i.87","spi":45223},{"ty":"te","id":"i.88","spi":45494},{"ty":"te","id":"i.89","spi":45743},{"ty":"te","id":"i.90","spi":46167},{"ty":"te","id":"i.91","spi":46343},{"ty":"te","id":"i.92","spi":46510},{"ty":"te","id":"i.93","spi":46768},{"ty":"te","id":"i.94","spi":47231},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":43322,"ei":43322,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":43323,"ei":43323,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":43324,"ei":43324,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":468.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.75,"tbls_bc":"#bdbdbd"}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":43326,"ei":43326,"sm":{"cell_pb_i":false,"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_pb":0.0,"cell_pr":0.0,"cell_pl_i":false,"cell_pl":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":43328,"ei":43328,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":358.5,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"cel